At a time when rights are embattled both locally and globally, the annual
event in Melbourne explored many of the topical issues facing both Australia
and countries in the region.

Jesuit Catholic priest Father Frank Brennan spoke about religion and rights.
He is a member of the expert panel set up by the Federal government to examine
the question of religious freedom, following the [legalization of same sex
marriage](https://globalvoices.org/2017/12/14/we-are-one-same-sex-marriage-
becomes-legal-down-under/) in Australia in 2017.

Frank had advocated a vote in favor of equal marriage during a [national
survey](https://globalvoices.org/2017/11/16/the-winner-is-same-sex-marriage-
equality-in-australia/).

In his presentation, he argued that national human rights legislation would
help to clarify religious rights, but doubted that would happen:

> A national Charter of human rights is still best way to balance rights incl
> freedom of religion â€“
> [@FrFrankBrennan](https://twitter.com/FrFrankBrennan?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> [#HumanRIghts18](https://twitter.com/hashtag/HumanRIghts18?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
>
> â€” Adam Fletcher (@ad_fletch) [July 19,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/ad_fletch/status/1020092809418702848?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

